11_linear_programming


  1. Question

    A thief is stealing xots and yivs. Each xot has a mass of 8 kilograms and a volume of 14 liters. Each yiv has a mass of 16 kilograms and a volume of 7 liters. The thief can carry a maximum mass of 128 kilograms and a maximum volume of 98 liters. The profit from each xot is $6.44 and the profit from each yiv is $5.35.

    For your convenience, those numbers are organized in the table below.

    attribute xot yiv capacity
    mass (kg) 8 16 128
    volume (L) 14 7 98
    profit ($) 6.44 5.35 \(\infty\)

    What is the maximum profit the thief can produce? (In dollars.)


    Solution

    This is an example of linear programming.

    Define \(x\) as number of xots and \(y\) as number of yivs. Write the constraints as inequalities.

    • Mass constraint: \(8x+16y \le 128\)
    • Volume constraint: \(14x+7y \le 98\)

    We can assume that optimal profit will occur at a boundary, so we can just consider the equations. \[8x+16y = 128\] \[14x+7y = 98\]

    If either equation has coefficients that all share a common factor, we can simplify by dividing both sides by the greatest common factor:

    \[1x+2y = 16\] \[2x+1y = 14\]

    We need to find the \(x\) intercepts and the \(y\) intercepts.

    To find the \(x\)-intercepts, set \(y\) to 0.

    • The \(x\)-intercept of the mass constraint: \[1x_{\text{int}1}+(2)(0) = 16 \] \[1x_{\text{int}1} = 16 \] \[x_{\text{int}1} = \frac{16}{1} = 16 \]

    • The \(x\)-intercept of the volume constraint:

    \[2x_{\text{int}2}+(1)(0) = 14 \] \[2x_{\text{int}2} = 14 \] \[x_{\text{int}2} = \frac{14}{2} = 7 \]

    To find the \(y\)-intercepts, set \(x\) to 0.

    • The \(y\)-intercept of the mass constraint: \[(1)(0)+(2)(y_{\text{int1}}) = 16 \] \[2y_{\text{int}1} = 16 \] \[y_{\text{int}1} = \frac{16}{2} = 8 \]

    • The \(y\)-intercept of the volume constraint:

    \[(2)(0)+(1)y_{\text{int2}} = 14 \] \[1y_{\text{int}2} = 14 \] \[y_{\text{int}2} = \frac{14}{1} = 14 \]

    To find the intersection of the constraints, I would recommend elimination. Multiply the equations to have matching coefficients for \(y\) terms.

    \[1x + 2y = 16\] \[4x + 2y = 28\] Subtract equations.

    \[3x + (0)y = 12\]

    Simplify.

    \[3x = 12\]

    Divide by 3.

    \[x = 4\]

    Plug \(x = 4\) into the first equation. Solve for \(y\).

    \[(1)(4)+2y = 16\] \[4+2y = 16\] \[2y = 12\] \[y = 6\]

    So, the intersection occurs at \((4,\,6)\).

    You can plot the boundaries and shade the feasible region.


    The maximum profit could occur at \((0,8)\) or \((4,6)\) or \((7,0)\).

    Find those profits, using \(P(x,y)=6.44x+5.35y\).

    \[P(0,8)=(6.44)(0)+(5.35)(8) = 42.8\] \[P(4,6)=(6.44)(4)+(5.35)(6) = 57.86\] \[P(7,0)=(6.44)(7)+(5.35)(0) = 45.08\]

    So, the maximum profit is $57.86.

    It might help to visualize this in 3D, with xots, yivs, and profit on the 3 axes. Sorry, I was not able to make a 3D plot show up here. But, we can add a third dimension by using a color ramp for profit. You can see that since our profit function is linear in \(x\) and linear in \(y\), the profit grows linearly as either xots or yivs are added. Another useful concept is an isoprofit line, which shows all the possible combinations of xots and yivs that would generate the same profit (see contour lines). Since profit is linear in both \(x\) and \(y\), we see the isoprofit lines are all parallel. Also, in this case, the isoprofit lines are not parallel to either constraint, so there will be only a single optimal choice.




  2. Question

    A thief is stealing xots and yivs. Each xot has a mass of 3 kilograms and a volume of 12 liters. Each yiv has a mass of 15 kilograms and a volume of 6 liters. The thief can carry a maximum mass of 45 kilograms and a maximum volume of 72 liters. The profit from each xot is $2.78 and the profit from each yiv is $7.95.

    For your convenience, those numbers are organized in the table below.

    attribute xot yiv capacity
    mass (kg) 3 15 45
    volume (L) 12 6 72
    profit ($) 2.78 7.95 \(\infty\)

    What is the maximum profit the thief can produce? (In dollars.)


    Solution

    This is an example of linear programming.

    Define \(x\) as number of xots and \(y\) as number of yivs. Write the constraints as inequalities.

    • Mass constraint: \(3x+15y \le 45\)
    • Volume constraint: \(12x+6y \le 72\)

    If either equation has coefficients that all share a common factor, we can simplify by dividing both sides by the greatest common factor:

    \[1x+5y = 15\] \[2x+1y = 12\]

    We need to find the \(x\) intercepts and the \(y\) intercepts.

    To find the \(x\)-intercepts, set \(y\) to 0.

    • The \(x\)-intercept of the mass constraint: \[1x_{\text{int}1}+(5)(0) = 15 \] \[1x_{\text{int}1} = 15 \] \[x_{\text{int}1} = \frac{15}{1} = 15 \]

    • The \(x\)-intercept of the volume constraint:

    \[2x_{\text{int}2}+(1)(0) = 12 \] \[2x_{\text{int}2} = 12 \] \[x_{\text{int}2} = \frac{12}{2} = 6 \]

    To find the \(y\)-intercepts, set \(x\) to 0.

    • The \(y\)-intercept of the mass constraint: \[(1)(0)+(5)(y_{\text{int1}}) = 15 \] \[5y_{\text{int}1} = 15 \] \[y_{\text{int}1} = \frac{15}{5} = 3 \]

    • The \(y\)-intercept of the volume constraint:

    \[(2)(0)+(1)y_{\text{int2}} = 12 \] \[1y_{\text{int}2} = 12 \] \[y_{\text{int}2} = \frac{12}{1} = 12 \]

    To find the intersection of the constraints, I would recommend elimination. Multiply the equations to have matching coefficients for \(y\) terms.

    \[1x + 5y = 15\] \[10x + 5y = 60\] Subtract equations.

    \[9x + (0)y = 45\]

    Simplify.

    \[9x = 45\]

    Divide by 9.

    \[x = 5\]

    Plug \(x = 5\) into the first equation. Solve for \(y\).

    \[(1)(5)+5y = 15\] \[5+5y = 15\] \[5y = 10\] \[y = 2\]

    So, the intersection occurs at \((5,\,2)\).

    You can plot the boundaries and shade the feasible region.


    The maximum profit could occur at \((0,3)\) or \((5,2)\) or \((6,0)\).

    Find those profits, using \(P(x,y)=2.78x+7.95y\).

    \[P(0,3)=(2.78)(0)+(7.95)(3) = 23.85\] \[P(5,2)=(2.78)(5)+(7.95)(2) = 29.8\] \[P(6,0)=(2.78)(6)+(7.95)(0) = 16.68\]

    So, the maximum profit is $29.80.

    It might help to visualize this in 3D, with xots, yivs, and profit on the 3 axes. Sorry, I was not able to make a 3D plot show up here. But, we can add a third dimension by using a color ramp for profit. You can see that since our profit function is linear in \(x\) and linear in \(y\), the profit grows linearly as either xots or yivs are added.   4. Question

    A thief is stealing xots and yivs. Each xot has a mass of 18 kilograms and a volume of 16 liters. Each yiv has a mass of 9 kilograms and a volume of 10 liters.     attribute xot yiv capacity
    mass (kg) 18 9 162
    volume (L) 16 10 160

    Divide by 2.

    \[x = 5\]

    So, the intersection occurs at \((5,\,8)\).

  5. Question

    A thief is stealing xots and yivs. Each xot has a mass of 7 kilograms and a volume of 9 liters. Each yiv has a mass of 14 kilograms and a volume of 12 liters. The thief can carry a maximum mass of 98 kilograms and a maximum volume of 108 liters. The profit from each xot is $3.82 and the profit from each yiv is $7.12.

    For your convenience, those numbers are organized in the table below.

    attribute xot yiv capacity
    mass (kg) 7 14 98
    volume (L) 9 12 108
    profit ($) 3.82 7.12 \(\infty\)

    What is the maximum profit the thief can produce? (In dollars.)


    Solution

    This is an example of linear programming.

    Define \(x\) as number of xots and \(y\) as number of yivs. Write the constraints as inequalities.

    • Mass constraint: \(7x+14y \le 98\)
    • Volume constraint: \(9x+12y \le 108\)

    \[1x+2y = 14\] \[3x+4y = 36\]

    We need to find the \(x\) intercepts and the \(y\) intercepts.

    To find the \(x\)-intercepts, set \(y\) to 0.

    • The \(x\)-intercept of the mass constraint: \[1x_{\text{int}1}+(2)(0) = 14 \] \[1x_{\text{int}1} = 14 \] \[x_{\text{int}1} = \frac{14}{1} = 14 \]

    • The \(x\)-intercept of the volume constraint:

    \[3x_{\text{int}2}+(4)(0) = 36 \] \[3x_{\text{int}2} = 36 \] \[x_{\text{int}2} = \frac{36}{3} = 12 \]

    To find the \(y\)-intercepts, set \(x\) to 0.

    • The \(y\)-intercept of the mass constraint: \[(1)(0)+(2)(y_{\text{int1}}) = 14 \] \[2y_{\text{int}1} = 14 \] \[y_{\text{int}1} = \frac{14}{2} = 7 \]

    • The \(y\)-intercept of the volume constraint:

    \[(3)(0)+(4)y_{\text{int2}} = 36 \] \[4y_{\text{int}2} = 36 \] \[y_{\text{int}2} = \frac{36}{4} = 9 \]

    To find the intersection of the constraints, I would recommend elimination. Multiply the equations to have matching coefficients for \(y\) terms.

    \[2x + 4y = 28\] \[3x + 4y = 36\] Subtract equations.

    \[1x + (0)y = 8\]

    Simplify.

    \[1x = 8\]

    Divide by 1.

    \[x = 8\]

    Plug \(x = 8\) into the first equation. Solve for \(y\).

    \[(1)(8)+2y = 14\] \[8+2y = 14\] \[2y = 6\] \[y = 3\]

    So, the intersection occurs at \((8,\,3)\).

    You can plot the boundaries and shade the feasible region.


    The maximum profit could occur at \((0,7)\) or \((8,3)\) or \((12,0)\).

    \[P(0,7)=(3.82)(0)+(7.12)(7) = 49.84\] \[P(8,3)=(3.82)(8)+(7.12)(3) = 51.92\] \[P(12,0)=(3.82)(12)+(7.12)(0) = 45.84\]

    So, the maximum profit is $51.92.

    It might help to visualize this in 3D, with xots, yivs, and profit on the 3 axes. Sorry, I was not able to make a 3D plot show up here. But, we can add a third dimension by using a color ramp for profit.   7. Question

    A thief is stealing xots and yivs. Each xot has a mass of 16 kilograms and a volume of 18 liters. Each yiv has a mass of 10 kilograms and a volume of 9 liters. The thief can carry a maximum mass of 160 kilograms and a maximum volume of 162 liters. The profit from each xot is $4.48 and the profit from each yiv is $3.

    For your convenience, those numbers are organized in the table below.

    attribute xot yiv capacity
    mass (kg) 16 10 160
    volume (L) 18 9 162
    profit ($) 4.48 3.00 \(\infty\)

    What is the maximum profit the thief can produce? (In dollars.)


    Solution

    This is an example of linear programming.

    Define \(x\) as number of xots and \(y\) as number of yivs. Write the constraints as inequalities.

    • Mass constraint: \(16x+10y \le 160\)
    • Volume constraint: \(18x+9y \le 162\)

    We can assume that optimal profit will occur at a boundary, so we can just consider the equations. \[16x+10y = 160\] \[18x+9y = 162\]

    \[8x+5y = 80\] \[2x+1y = 18\]

    We need to find the \(x\) intercepts and the \(y\) intercepts.

    To find the \(x\)-intercepts, set \(y\) to 0.

    • The \(x\)-intercept of the mass constraint: \[8x_{\text{int}1}+(5)(0) = 80 \] \[8x_{\text{int}1} = 80 \] \[x_{\text{int}1} = \frac{80}{8} = 10 \]

    • The \(x\)-intercept of the volume constraint:

    \[2x_{\text{int}2}+(1)(0) = 18 \] \[2x_{\text{int}2} = 18 \] \[x_{\text{int}2} = \frac{18}{2} = 9 \]

    To find the \(y\)-intercepts, set \(x\) to 0.

    • The \(y\)-intercept of the mass constraint: \[(8)(0)+(5)(y_{\text{int1}}) = 80 \] \[5y_{\text{int}1} = 80 \] \[y_{\text{int}1} = \frac{80}{5} = 16 \]

    • The \(y\)-intercept of the volume constraint:

    \[(2)(0)+(1)y_{\text{int2}} = 18 \] \[1y_{\text{int}2} = 18 \] \[y_{\text{int}2} = \frac{18}{1} = 18 \]

    \[8x + 5y = 80\] \[10x + 5y = 90\] Subtract equations.

    \[2x + (0)y = 10\]

    Simplify.

    \[2x = 10\]

    Divide by 2.

    \[x = 5\]

    Plug \(x = 5\) into the first equation. Solve for \(y\).

    \[(8)(5)+5y = 80\] \[40+5y = 80\] \[5y = 40\] \[y = 8\]

    So, the intersection occurs at \((5,\,8)\).

    You can plot the boundaries and shade the feasible region.


    The maximum profit could occur at \((0,16)\) or \((5,8)\) or \((9,0)\).

    Find those profits, using \(P(x,y)=4.48x+3y\).

    \[P(0,16)=(4.48)(0)+(3)(16) = 48\] \[P(5,8)=(4.48)(5)+(3)(8) = 46.4\] \[P(9,0)=(4.48)(9)+(3)(0) = 40.32\]

    So, the maximum profit is $48.00.

    It might help to visualize this in 3D, with xots, yivs, and profit on the 3 axes. Sorry, I was not able to make a 3D plot show up here. But, we can add a third dimension by using a color ramp for profit. You can see that since our profit function is linear in \(x\) and linear in \(y\), the profit grows linearly as either xots or yivs are added. Another useful concept is an isoprofit line, which shows all the possible combinations of xots and yivs that would generate the same profit (see contour lines). Since profit is linear in both \(x\) and \(y\), we see the isoprofit lines are all parallel. Also, in this case, the isoprofit lines are not parallel to either constraint, so there will be only a single optimal choice.




  8. Question

    A thief is stealing xots and yivs. Each xot has a mass of 18 kilograms and a volume of 12 liters. Each yiv has a mass of 10 kilograms and a volume of 20 liters. The thief can carry a maximum mass of 180 kilograms and a maximum volume of 240 liters. The profit from each xot is $9.27 and the profit from each yiv is $6.83.

    For your convenience, those numbers are organized in the table below.

    attribute xot yiv capacity
    mass (kg) 18 10 180
    volume (L) 12 20 240
    profit ($) 9.27 6.83 \(\infty\)

    What is the maximum profit the thief can produce? (In dollars.)


    Solution

    This is an example of linear programming.

    Define \(x\) as number of xots and \(y\) as number of yivs. Write the constraints as inequalities.

    • Mass constraint: \(18x+10y \le 180\)
    • Volume constraint: \(12x+20y \le 240\)

    We can assume that optimal profit will occur at a boundary, so we can just consider the equations. \[18x+10y = 180\] \[12x+20y = 240\]

    If either equation has coefficients that all share a common factor, we can simplify by dividing both sides by the greatest common factor:

    \[9x+5y = 90\] \[3x+5y = 60\]

    We need to find the \(x\) intercepts and the \(y\) intercepts.

    To find the \(x\)-intercepts, set \(y\) to 0.

    • The \(x\)-intercept of the mass constraint: \[9x_{\text{int}1}+(5)(0) = 90 \] \[9x_{\text{int}1} = 90 \] \[x_{\text{int}1} = \frac{90}{9} = 10 \]

    • The \(x\)-intercept of the volume constraint:

    \[3x_{\text{int}2}+(5)(0) = 60 \] \[3x_{\text{int}2} = 60 \] \[x_{\text{int}2} = \frac{60}{3} = 20 \]

    To find the \(y\)-intercepts, set \(x\) to 0.

    • The \(y\)-intercept of the mass constraint: \[(9)(0)+(5)(y_{\text{int1}}) = 90 \] \[5y_{\text{int}1} = 90 \] \[y_{\text{int}1} = \frac{90}{5} = 18 \]

    • The \(y\)-intercept of the volume constraint:

    \[(3)(0)+(5)y_{\text{int2}} = 60 \] \[5y_{\text{int}2} = 60 \] \[y_{\text{int}2} = \frac{60}{5} = 12 \]

    To find the intersection of the constraints, I would recommend elimination. Multiply the equations to have matching coefficients for \(y\) terms.

    \[9x + 5y = 90\] \[3x + 5y = 60\] Subtract equations.

    \[6x + (0)y = 30\]

    Simplify.

    \[6x = 30\]

    Divide by 6.

    \[x = 5\]

    Plug \(x = 5\) into the first equation. Solve for \(y\).

    \[(9)(5)+5y = 90\] \[45+5y = 90\] \[5y = 45\] \[y = 9\]

    So, the intersection occurs at \((5,\,9)\).

    You can plot the boundaries and shade the feasible region.


    The maximum profit could occur at \((0,12)\) or \((5,9)\) or \((10,0)\).

    Find those profits, using \(P(x,y)=9.27x+6.83y\).

    \[P(0,12)=(9.27)(0)+(6.83)(12) = 81.96\] \[P(5,9)=(9.27)(5)+(6.83)(9) = 107.82\] \[P(10,0)=(9.27)(10)+(6.83)(0) = 92.7\]

    So, the maximum profit is $107.82.

    It might help to visualize this in 3D, with xots, yivs, and profit on the 3 axes. Sorry, I was not able to make a 3D plot show up here. But, we can add a third dimension by using a color ramp for profit. You can see that since our profit function is linear in \(x\) and linear in \(y\), the profit grows linearly as either xots or yivs are added. Another useful concept is an isoprofit line, which shows all the possible combinations of xots and yivs that would generate the same profit (see contour lines). Since profit is linear in both \(x\) and \(y\), we see the isoprofit lines are all parallel. Also, in this case, the isoprofit lines are not parallel to either constraint, so there will be only a single optimal choice.
